> You observe build errors that nobody else has, so your exact environment needs to be investigated for the source of the issue

How can I investigate it? Do you have any idea?
What tools are likely the cause of the error?

Have you tried a clean `git clone ...` and ran make from that directory? Have you checked if you have all prerequisites and they are up to date? If you build nvim everyday, what changed on your machine on that day? Can you cherry-pick the commit?

> Please see the following output as its from the master bracnh of neovim and I get the same error.
> 
> The output

> ```
> ⌘ Applications » git clone --depth=1 https://github.com/neovim/neovim.git neovim_master
> ```

I am not sure that it should matter, but try a full clone (i.e., remove `--depth=1`.

One other thought: since there are so many variables involved, you may have more luck [in chat](https://app.element.io/#/room/#neovim:matrix.org). Look for dundargoc in particular. I have found him to be helpful about builds.

The issue is caused by line-endings not matching the regex patterns used  `gen_declarations.lua`. For example [this pattern](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/66f02ee1fea2cf3c033e48e58bd49e8b81c7a11e/src/gen/gen_declarations.lua#L153-L154) checks for `\n` which does not match if you set `core.autocrlf` to `true`.

Steps to reproduce:

```bash 
git config --global core.autocrlf true
rm -rf ./src
git reset --hard master
make distclean
make CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release 
```

This will work
```bash 
git config --global core.autocrlf false #OR input
rm -rf ./src
git reset --hard master
make distclean
make CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release 
```
Is there a good reason to set `core.autcrlf` to true (on macOS)?

> Is there a good reason to set core.autcrlf to true (on macOS)?

I set it as I was working on a flutter project that had a messed up line-end encoding with each line having a `^M` at the end.

I believe that we should guard against it. Feel free to close if you disagree.

> I set it as I was working on a flutter project

That is not a good reason to set it globally, so I disagree that we should guard against it.
If we can guard against non-obvious problems with a small amount of isolated code, we should. @khalidchawtany feel free to send a PR that adds a sanity check to our CMakeLists.txt
